javamockit wrote:
&gt; Consider you want to unit test the following method:
&gt; 
&gt; public int doBusinessOp(Data data) {
&gt;   ...
&gt;   int sum = new ServiceX().addItems(data.getItems());
&gt;   ...
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Without changing doBusinessOp, how would you isolate it from the
&gt; dependency on class ServiceX?
&gt; 
&gt; I recently created a small tool that allows such tests to be written.
&gt; It seems the only other way would be to use AspectJ or one of the
&gt; XML-based AOP frameworks.
&gt; 
&gt; With the new tool you could write (in a JUnit TestCase):
&gt; 
&gt; public void testDoBusinessOp() {
&gt;   Mockit.redefineMethods(ServiceX.class, new Object() {
&gt;     public int addItems(List items) { 
&gt;       assertNotNull(items); return 0;
&gt;     }
&gt;   });
&gt; 
&gt;   ... create data, call doBusinessOp, assert result ...
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Project home page at jmockit.dev.java.net.
&gt; 
&gt; What do you think?

I can see this being much more useful /outside/ of testing; it&#39;s 
analagous to Smalltalk, Objective-C, and Ruby&#39;s way of overriding 
without extending. But it would probably just make me more sad that I&#39;m 
using Java instead of a more elegant, dynamic language... :(
